    "summary": "Good approach, one caveat on 现象仁 vs 仁",
    "content": "**Yes, good approach.** The three-layer format (original, glossed English, then plain English) is standard for scholarly translations of Chinese philosophical texts and will feel familiar to the target audience.\n\n**One caveat specific to this collection**: The author deliberately distinguishes between classical terms (仁, 义, 礼) and their phenomenal counterparts (现象仁, 现象义, 现象礼). The glossing format must make this distinction visible. On first occurrence, the reader needs to see both:\n\n- 仁 → \"humaneness (仁, ren)\" — the classical/metaphysical concept\n- 现象仁 → \"phenomenal humaneness (现象仁)\" — the author's coinage for the lived experience\n\nAfter first introduction, \"humaneness\" alone should refer to the classical concept, and \"phenomenal humaneness\" to the author's concept. This distinction is the engine of the 道德仁义礼 reversal argument -- if the reader cannot tell which one is being discussed at any given point, the reversal will not land.\n\nThe risk of cluttering is real in the 道德仁义礼 passage specifically, because the author introduces ten terms in rapid succession (道, 德, 仁, 义, 礼, and their five 现象 counterparts). My suggestion: gloss all ten on first occurrence in a short block, then immediately provide a brief reference table (as a footnote or inline list) so the reader can look back. After that, use plain English only. This front-loads the terminological overhead into one place rather than scattering it across the argument."
  }
}
